snippet.textDisplay: I enjoyed this movie, but it was such a mess. It seems that Abrams was trying to appease everyone, which is not a good thing. You know what was great about George Lucas? He didn't give a flying fuck about what people think about his movies, he wasn't trying to appease anyone, he was always making movies as he wanted. In fact, when Lucas started making "A New Hope", many people were laughing at him, but he didn't care, he finished his work, he released the movie and people loved it!  When he made "The Phantom Menace", many "fans" started insulting him, calling his creation  "a garbage", but Lucas didn't give a fuck! He finished the prequel trilogy, and you know what? It is great! The problem with "The Rise of Skywalker" is that JJ was trying to make both sides of Star Wars fanbase happy, but instead he made us all confused. I still like it, but I was expecting something better.

THEN maybe the last movie might have had a better set up. I dunno. I enjoyed it as a film, but I didn't care for the story, and I am not a fan of the ending.

The prequels are still bad, and the awfulness of the newest movies doesn't lessen that...
Episode 7 was directed by "Darth Plagiarist", aka Jar Jar Abrams who's never seen someone else's better work that he wasn't willing to rip off to lesser effect.
Episode 8 was clearly written with Roundhead Johnson's loose stool water and is without question the worst Star Wars property ever made, even surpassing the Holiday Special in awfulness.
Episode 9 is just the exhausted incontinent leavings of a franchise that's been completely raped of all good will for 20+ years now.


Disney, and even before them LucasFilm, has gone out of its way to ignore and ultimately "erase from canon" all of the books, comics, cartoons, games, etc etc etc that have been widely renowned for their quality and entertainment value, solely to just go back to the same story and characters and ruin what used to be good about them... Then when they supposedly do "try something new" (but not really), the preposterous mismanagement clearly had no overarching narrative in mind, so they kinda-sorta-maybe make some cliffhanger story threads in Ep7, but then bring in the angsty teenage art student douche to direct Ep8 and completely throw away everything built in Ep7 while dropping a hot steaming shit on the franchise to "subvert expectations"... Well, he got that right, not many people go to Star Wars movies expecting to satisfy a fecalphilia fetish other than Roundhead Johnson apparently...
So Ep9 didn't have a chance, it had to try to undo the utter failure of Ep8 while re-weaving the tapestry of utterly shredded plot threads back together into something even reasonably coherent, and unfortunately for all involved it just couldn't be done.

snippet.textDisplay:
Rey vs. Kilo Ren suddenly reminds me of the same problem Pokemon rivals have had in all the games after Gold and Silver (except maybe the one with the green hair). Vader was always a big scary threat who would beat Luke each time they met. Blue/Gary and the red haired guy from Gold/Silver were always scary and threatening because they were always beating other trainers even if you beat them (as a little kid, you might lose a few times).

Nowadays, every single "rival" you have is some plucky sidekick who tags along with you, making you the scary threatening one. They're always just like "Ooh! I wanna see if I've gotten stronger--Oh no you beat me! I'll get stronger!" Always with a smile on their face. And in Star Wars, Rey is always beating Kilo Ren with no trouble.

snippet.textDisplay:
Ok, how to fix this trainwreck of a trilogy.

1) Start episode 7 following Rey and her getting the Millennium Falcon, where she finds Han and Chewie, who guide her to the new Rebel Alliance.
2) Have Finn show up in the second act of episode 7, and follow him around as he starts to feel a connection to the force, which in turn makes Rey sense that she also has a connection to the force as well.
3) Episode 7 ends with Han dying, the new death star being destroyed, and Kylo Ren pursuing Rey, Finn and Chewie as they hear a force user to come to a planet to train to become jedi.

Episode 8:

1) Throw out all the shit that doesn't need to be there, and focus on Rey becoming proficient in the force and Finn learning how to become a jedi knight.
2) Second act focuses on Finn returning to the rebel alliance and taking on smuggling jobs and espionage missions.
3) Third act Rey goes to find Kylo, and the two fight even though he is the superior fighter. Kylo defeats Rey and tells her about her true lineage to Darth Sidious. Rey is then left defeated as Finn and Chewie come to her rescue and the trio escape. Rey is then visited by the force ghosts of Qui-Gon, Obi-Wan, Yoda, and Anakin Skywalker. They tell her to go back to Luke, who will complete her training to become a full fledged Jedi Knight.

Episode 9:

1)Kylo turns completly over to the dark side and becomes Darth Ren, and we learn his master is none other than the ghost of Darth Sideous. Meanwhile, Rey heads back to finish her training with Luke, as well as Obi-Wan and Yoda to give her guidance. She finishes her training by building her own lightsaber and setting out to quell her own fears. As act 1 ends we see Luke become a force ghost, and joining the other powerful jedi in the background.

2) Rey meets up with the rebels as they are preparing to launch a final assault on the first order, led by Poe and that asian chick, Rey learns of Leia's death and vows that she will destroy the sith and bring balance back to the force. Finn and Chewie are tasked with leading the assault and Rey is tasked with finding Darth Ren and destroying him.

3) Act three is the final battle, with Chewie and Poe dogfighting and Finn leading a squad of rebels onto the main star destroyer to cripple the comms of the first order. As this is going on, Rey and Darth Ren are having an intense duel to the death, all while Sideous is feeling the hate flow through rey, and sees her as his new apprentice. Just then, Darth Ren shocks her with lightning, forcing her down and starts to attack ferociously. The battle reges until Rey gets the upper hand, knocks out Rens lightsaber, and uses the force to turn his mind into mush. She then uses her powers to erase Sideous from existence. She then feels a spark in Kylo, and with his last words before dying from his injuries, he says that he was the last skywalker, and that it is up to her to keep balance to the force. Finn knocks out the comms and Chewie starts destroying the first orders ships. The rebels win the battle and the final scene is Rey burning the now dead Ben Solo in a funeral pyre. As Rey turns she sees the force ghosts of all those who trained her and she heads off to form a new jedi order.

snippet.textDisplay:
Okay, so I just saw this movie a day after this review came out (I didn't watch it till after I'd seen the movie) and I HATED IT. After I cooled down a bit... I still didn't like it.


That said, I agree with the point you made at the end. The Star Wars movies may have taken a major hit for now, but that doesn't mean Star Wars won't live on in other ways like it has before. TV shows, video games, comics, novels; they'll always be a way for someone to build and expand upon the world laid out in the original movies. And who knows, maybe with some more thought and better planning, Disney can make better Star Wars movies down the road. But the bottom line is, Star Wars isn't going anywhere. If superhero comics are modern Greek mythology, then I'd say Star Wars is modern Arthurian mythology. They'll be variations and contradictions, but myths are what YOU decide they are. It's not like history where "this is what happened and we can't change it." YOU decide what is and isn't part of the mythos. Some might include these new movies, some might ignore them; but ALL of them are entitled to their opinion because everyone gets to see the stories in their own way. So to all Star Wars fans, whether you like the originals the best, the prequels the best, the new ones the best, or whatever,


May the Force be With You.
